column1: Source: Julia Gelatt, Hamutal Bernstein, and Heather Koball, "State Immigration Policy Resource," Washington, DC: Urban Institute, May 2017, http://urban.org/features/state-immigration-policy-resource.

Original data sources: US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Library: 287(g) - Memorandums of Agreement/Understanding and 287(g) - Memorandums of Agreement/Understanding (Old); "Delegation of Immigration Authority Section 287(g) Immigration and Nationality Act," ICE, accessed April 21, 2017, https://www.ice.gov/factsheets/287g.

Notes: 287(g) deputizes local law enforcement to perform certain functions of federal immigration officials, including accessing federal immigration databases and arresting and detaining individuals for suspected immigration violations. The task force model, which ended in 2012, allowed officials to act in the community. The jail model allows officials to perform immigration enforcement functions in jails.

We only list 287(g) agreements signed by state-wide agencies or by the counties with the highest immigrant population in the state (defined as thouse counties with the largest numbers of foreign-born individuals, counting all those whose foreign-born population totals to 50 percent of the overall foreign-born population in the state).
The first 287(g) agreement was signed in 2002, so we do not include 2000 and 2001 in this table.
